<quote author="Dembski">Natural selection is widely supposed to be an information ratchet that gradually accumulates the information organisms need to acquire novel adaptations. Yet natural selection is nothing of the sort. The Darwinian mechanism of natural selection and random variation is a low-level trial-and-error method for solving routine problems that is unequipped to handle the innovative problems that biological systems have solved in the course of natural history. 
</quote>

Before I embark on exposing the flaws in Dembski's 'reasoning', let me first point out that the simple processes of variation and selection have been shown to be sufficient to increase the information in the genome. As such, there is no 'information problem' in biology. Furthermore, let's point out that since 'design' is based on the concept that 'processes of regularity and chance' cannot explain 'x', the fact that at least in principle such processes can explain the information in the genome, 'design' has been effectively blocked.

<quote author="Dembski">Darwinism and evolutionary biology more generally, committed as they are to unguided material mechanisms, do not have the resources to solve biology's information problem. This talk will indicate why biology's information problem is unresolvable apart from intelligent design.</quote>

As Dembski has pointed out "Intelligent causes act by making a choice" and thus he also admits that processes such as variation and selection are 'intelligent causes'. 

<quote author="Dembski">The principal characteristic of intelligent causation is directed contingency, or what we call choice. Whenever an intelligent cause acts, it chooses from a range of competing possibilities. </quote>

In fact, Darwin understood the similarities between natural and artificial selection, which in many ways are very similar. In the latter case, an intelligence determines who or what is allowed to reproduce, in the former case, it is the environment itself which chooses from a range of competing possibilities. There is nothing much different between the two processes.

Since 'design' is blocked as a competing explanation because processes of regularity and chance can, at least in principle, explain information in the genome and because Intelligent Design proponents refuse to propose a competing hypothesis, Intelligent Design has to change its argument from 'evolutionary processes cannot explain information' to 'evolutionary processes cannot explain innovative solutions'. While the latter concept is even hard to quantify than ID's concept of information, actual evidence strongly contradicts Dembski's claims here.

