Evolution and Innovation

A good example of evolution and innovation can be found in the folding of RNA into secondary structures.

The work by Peter Schuster, Walter Fontana, and many others involved the RNA networks. In their experiments they showed some of the interesting features and consequences of the phenotype genotype mapping in RNA, they showed that like for proteins, there are few common structures which seem to span all of sequence space and which are well connected versus many uncommon structures which often tend to be less well connected. The genotype phenotype mapping and the presence of large neutral networks suggest that neutral evolution plays an important part during periods of stasis followed by periods of innovation when mutations reach new secondary structures. These characteristics may explain why evolution has been so successful.

Some of their relevant findings are that

1. More sequences than structures

2. Few common and many rare structures.

3. Common structures are found almost everywhere in sequence space.

4. Neutral networks of common structures extend over whole sequence space.

<quote>The existence of extended and connected neutral networks in RNA sequence space was proven by an elegant experiment recently published by Erik Schultes and David Bartel. They designed an RNA sequence which forms two known structures (of chain length (l = 88) with different catalytic activities, an RNA ligase evolved in the laboratory and a natural cleavage ribozyme isolated from hepatitis delta virus RNA. The two structures have no base pair in common. Folding the synthesized chimeric sequence into structures yielded indeed both activities, although they were substantially weaker than those of the reference ribozymes, the ligase and the cleavage ribozyme, respectively. Only two or three selected point mutations or base pair exchanges are required, however, to reach full catalytic efficiency. Still, the two optimzed RNA molecules have a Hamming distance around forty from their reference sequences. Then, Schultes and Bartel explored further the mutational neighborhoods and found neutral paths of Hamming distance about 40, by preparing and analyzing series of RNA sequences, in which neighboring sequences differ in a single base or base pair only. Without interruption these neutral paths lead from the RNA with both catalytic activities to the two reference ribozymes.
</quote>

