In typical ID fashion, Dembski answers his own question about where the information comes from and yet pretends that there is somehow a need for 'intelligent design' to give evolution a never-ending future. I am sure that the dinosaurs are not too impressed by this argument.

<quote>Dembski suggested in his lecture that there is a whole realm of biological complexities that Darwin didn't know about and that there has to be an intelligent design within evolution to create variation and change, giving evolution a never-ending future.

Evolution is all about borrowing information from previous evolutionary instances, which is why such complex biological structures and functions can be built, he said. But what we need to ask ourselves is: where does that information come from? </quote>

<b>Source:</b> Christina Kruse <a href="http://www.baylor.edu/lariat/news.php?action=story&story=53869">Professor's views test Darwinian evolution theory</a> The Lariat Online, Oct. 22, 2008.

In other words, Dembski admits that evolutionary processes can in fact explain complex biological structures and functions but 'argues', no that's granting too much, asserts that the source of information needs to be 'intelligently designed'. As I have already shown, natural selection, matches the requirements for 'intelligence' quite well, a finding which is not novel since Wesley Elsberry already pointed out that

<quote author="Wesley Elsberry">"The apparent, but unstated, logic behind the move from design to agency can be given as follows:

1. There exists an attribute in common of some subset of objects known to be designed by an intelligent agent.
       
2. This attribute is never found in objects known not to be designed by an intelligent agent.
       
3. The attribute encapsulates the property of directed contingency or choice.
       
4.For all objects, if this attribute is found in an object, then we may conclude that the object was designed by an intelligent agent.

"This is an inductive argument. Notice that by the second step, one must eliminate from consideration precisely those biological phenomena which Dembski wishes to categorize. In order to conclude intelligent agency for biological examples, the possibility that intelligent agency is not operative is excluded a priori. One large problem is that directed contingency or choice is not solely an attribute of events due to the intervention of an intelligent agent.

The "actualization-exclusion-specification" triad mentioned above also fits natural selection rather precisely. One might thus conclude that Dembski's argument establishes that natural selection can be recognized  as an intelligent agent. " </quote>

And as Ryan Nichols has pointed out in his devastating review of Intelligent Design:

<quote author="Ryan Nichols">Before I proceed, however, I note that Dembski makes an important concession to his critics. He refuses to make the second assumption noted above. When the EF implies that certain systems are intelligently designed, Dembski does not think it follows that there is some intelligent designer or other. He says that, "even though in practice inferring design is the first step in identifying an intelligent agent, taken by itself design does not require that such an agent be posited. The notion of design that emerges from the design inference must not be confused with intelligent agency" </quote>


<b>Source</b>: Ryan Nichols, <b>Scientific content, testability, and the vacuity of Intelligent Design theory</b> The American Catholic philosophical quarterly , 2003 , vol. 77 , no 4 , pp. 591 - 611.

Sufficient to conclude that Dembski, other than asserting that his faith guides him in proposing a supernatural 'designer', has admitted that processes of regularity and chance are sufficient to explain the information and complexity found in living cells, and as thus has blocked any hope for a design inference. Worse, he has failed to explain how Intelligent Design 'explains' these findings. When asked previously, his response was quite helpful in understanding why ID is doomed to remain without scientific content:


